</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Transthoracic echocardiography (<abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr>) is a critical tool in the field of clinical cardiology. It often serves as one of the first-line imaging modalities in the evaluation of cardiac disease owing to its low cost, portability, widespread availability, lack of ionizing radiation, and ability to evaluate both anatomy and function of the heart. Consequently, a large majority of patients undergoing a cardiac computed tomography (CT) or magnetic resonance (MR) imaging examination will have a <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> available for review. Therefore, it is imperative that cardiac imagers be familiar with the fundamentals of a routine <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> examination and common <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> pitfalls and limitations that may lead to a referral for cardiac CT or MR imaging. The four standard <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> windows and their corresponding views will be discussed and the relevant anatomy highlighted. Common pitfalls and limitations of <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> will be highlighted using cardiac CT and MR imaging as the problem-solving modality. In this article, we have categorized the relevant pitfalls and limitations of <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> into four broad categories: <i>(a)</i> masses and mass mimics (crista terminalis, eustachian valve, right ventricle moderator band, atrioventricular groove fat, left ventricular band [or left ventricular false tendon], hiatal hernia, caseous calcification of the mitral annulus, lipomatous hypertrophy of the interatrial septum, cardiac tumors), <i>(b)</i> poorly visualized apical lesions (aneurysm, thrombus, infarct, and hypertrophic and other nonischemic cardiomyopathies), <i>(c)</i> evaluation for ascending thoracic aortic dissections (false positive, false negative, dissecting aneurysms), and <i>(d)</i> pericardial disease (acute and chronic/constrictive pericarditis, pericardial tamponade, pericardial cysts and diverticula, congenital absence of the pericardium).</div><div role="paragraph"><i>Online supplemental material is available for this article.</i></div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2017</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2017160105">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2017160105">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160105/asset/images/large/rg.2017160105.fig1.jpeg" height="1596" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig1" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span>. Three-dimensional (3D) volume-rendered image of the chest and heart demonstrates placements of the ultrasound transducer used to obtained the four standard windows during a routine <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> examination. <i>A</i> = apical, <i>C</i> = subcostal, <i>P</i> = parasternal, <i>S</i> = suprasternal.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160105&amp;id=fig1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160105/asset/images/large/rg.2017160105.fig2a.jpeg" height="726" width="670" aria-labelledby="fig2a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span>. Normal suprasternal window from a <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> examination <b>(a)</b> and corresponding CT angiogram reformatted to match the <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> <b>(b)</b>. <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>BR</i> = brachiocephalic artery, <i>LCC</i> = left common carotid artery, <i>LSC</i> = left subclavian artery, <i>RPA</i> = right pulmonary artery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160105&amp;id=fig2a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160105/asset/images/large/rg.2017160105.fig2b.jpeg" height="726" width="555" aria-labelledby="fig2b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span>. Normal suprasternal window from a <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> examination <b>(a)</b> and corresponding CT angiogram reformatted to match the <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> <b>(b)</b>. <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>BR</i> = brachiocephalic artery, <i>LCC</i> = left common carotid artery, <i>LSC</i> = left subclavian artery, <i>RPA</i> = right pulmonary artery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160105&amp;id=fig2b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160105/asset/images/large/rg.2017160105.fig3a.jpeg" height="516" width="693" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span>. Normal parasternal long-axis view from a <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> examination <b>(a)</b> and corresponding CT angiogram reformatted to match the <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> <b>(b)</b>. <i>AAo</i> = ascending thoracic aorta, <i>AV</i> = aortic valve, <i>DAo</i> = descending thoracic aorta, <i>IVS</i> = interventricular septum, <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle, <i>LVI</i> = left ventricular inferolateral wall, <i>LVOT</i> = left ventricular outflow tract, <i>MV</i> = mitral valve, <i>P</i> = pericardial effusion, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160105&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160105/asset/images/large/rg.2017160105.fig3b.jpeg" height="516" width="632" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span>. Normal parasternal long-axis view from a <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> examination <b>(a)</b> and corresponding CT angiogram reformatted to match the <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> <b>(b)</b>. <i>AAo</i> = ascending thoracic aorta, <i>AV</i> = aortic valve, <i>DAo</i> = descending thoracic aorta, <i>IVS</i> = interventricular septum, <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle, <i>LVI</i> = left ventricular inferolateral wall, <i>LVOT</i> = left ventricular outflow tract, <i>MV</i> = mitral valve, <i>P</i> = pericardial effusion, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160105&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160105/asset/images/large/rg.2017160105.fig4a.jpeg" height="664" width="746" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span>. Normal parasternal right ventricular inflow-outflow view from a <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> examination <b>(a)</b> and corresponding CT angiogram reformatted to match the <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> <b>(b)</b>. <i>CS</i> = coronary sinus, <i>EV</i> = eustachian valve, <i>IVC</i> = inferior vena cava, <i>RA</i> = right atrium, <i>TV</i> = tricuspid valve.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160105&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160105/asset/images/large/rg.2017160105.fig4b.jpeg" height="664" width="578" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span>. Normal parasternal right ventricular inflow-outflow view from a <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> examination <b>(a)</b> and corresponding CT angiogram reformatted to match the <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> <b>(b)</b>. <i>CS</i> = coronary sinus, <i>EV</i> = eustachian valve, <i>IVC</i> = inferior vena cava, <i>RA</i> = right atrium, <i>TV</i> = tricuspid valve.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160105&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160105/asset/images/large/rg.2017160105.fig5a.jpeg" height="579" width="553" aria-labelledby="fig5a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span>. Normal parasternal short-axis views from a <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> examination and corresponding CT angiograms reformatted to match the <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> at the level of the aortic valve <b>(a, b)</b>, a basal left ventricular section <b>(c, d)</b>, and a middle left ventricular section <b>(e, f)</b>, respectively. Note the bifid medial papillary muscle seen on the middle left ventricular section. <i>Ant MV</i> = anterior mitral valve leaflet, <i>IAS</i> = interatrial septum, <i>LAA</i> = left atrial appendage, <i>LC</i> = left coronary leaflet of the aortic valve, <i>L-PM</i> = lateral papillary muscle, <i>M-PM</i> = medial papillary muscle, <i>NC</i> = noncoronary leaflet of the aortic valve, <i>PA</i> = pulmonary artery, <i>Post MV</i> = posterior mitral valve leaflet, <i>PV</i> = pulmonary valve, <i>RC</i> = right coronary leaflet of the aortic valve, <i>TV</i> = tricuspid valve.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160105&amp;id=fig5a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160105/asset/images/large/rg.2017160105.fig5b.jpeg" height="579" width="645" aria-labelledby="fig5b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span>. Normal parasternal short-axis views from a <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> examination and correspondin