class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160105/asset/images/large/rg.2017160105.fig8a.jpeg" height="811" width="561" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span>. Normal apical long-axis (or apical three-chamber) view from a <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> examination <b>(a)</b> and corresponding CT angiogram reformatted to match the <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> <b>(b)</b>. <i>Ao</i> = ascending thoracic aorta, <i>AV</i> = aortic valve, <i>DAo</i> = descending thoracic aorta, <i>MV</i> = mitral valve.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160105&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160105/asset/images/large/rg.2017160105.fig8b.jpeg" height="811" width="464" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span>. Normal apical long-axis (or apical three-chamber) view from a <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> examination <b>(a)</b> and corresponding CT angiogram reformatted to match the <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> <b>(b)</b>. <i>Ao</i> = ascending thoracic aorta, <i>AV</i> = aortic valve, <i>DAo</i> = descending thoracic aorta, <i>MV</i> = mitral valve.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160105&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160105/asset/images/large/rg.2017160105.fig9a.jpeg" height="592" width="673" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span>. Normal subcostal four-chamber view from a <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> examination <b>(a)</b> and corresponding CT angiogram reformatted to match the <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> <b>(b)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160105&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160105/asset/images/large/rg.2017160105.fig9b.jpeg" height="592" width="802" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span>. Normal subcostal four-chamber view from a <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> examination <b>(a)</b> and corresponding CT angiogram reformatted to match the <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> <b>(b)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160105&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160105/asset/images/large/rg.2017160105.fig10a.jpeg" height="674" width="665" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span>. Normal subcostal inferior vena cava <i>(IVC)</i> view from a <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> examination <b>(a)</b> and corresponding CT angiogram reformatted to match the <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> <b>(b)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160105&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160105/asset/images/large/rg.2017160105.fig10b.jpeg" height="674" width="459" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span>. Normal subcostal inferior vena cava <i>(IVC)</i> view from a <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> examination <b>(a)</b> and corresponding CT angiogram reformatted to match the <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> <b>(b)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160105&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160105/asset/images/large/rg.2017160105.fig11.jpeg" height="1476" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig11" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11</span>. Cutaway view of the right atrium. The crista terminalis (arrowheads) is a muscular ridge in the posterolateral right atrial wall that separates the smooth and muscular portions of the right atrium. <b>*</b> = fossa ovalis, open arrow = thebesian valve, solid arrow = eustachian valve, <i>IVC</i> = inferior vena cava, <i>SVC</i> = superior vena cava. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference 6.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160105&amp;id=fig11">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160105/asset/images/large/rg.2017160105.fig12a.jpeg" height="729" width="659" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span>. Prominent crista terminalis in an 86-year-old woman who presented with new-onset arrhythmia. <b>(a)</b> Coned-down apical four-chamber view from <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> demonstrates a hyperechoic mass (arrow) in the posterior right atrial wall. <b>(b)</b> Four-chamber reformatted electrocardiographically (ECG)–gated CT angiogram shows the suspected right atrial mass (arrow) to be a prominent crista terminalis, on the basis of location, appearance, and long-term stability (prior images not shown). Note that most experienced echocardiographers are well aware of this common anatomic variant and will assume the correct diagnosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160105&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160105/asset/images/large/rg.2017160105.fig12b.jpeg" height="729" width="566" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span>. Prominent crista terminalis in an 86-year-old woman who presented with new-onset arrhythmia. <b>(a)</b> Coned-down apical four-chamber view from <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> demonstrates a hyperechoic mass (arrow) in the posterior right atrial wall. <b>(b)</b> Four-chamber reformatted electrocardiographically (ECG)–gated CT angiogram shows the suspected right atrial mass (arrow) to be a prominent crista terminalis, on the basis of location, appearance, and long-term stability (prior images not shown). Note that most experienced echocardiographers are well aware of this common anatomic variant and will assume the correct diagnosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160105&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160105/asset/images/large/rg.2017160105.fig13a.jpeg" height="473" width="784" aria-labelledby="fig13a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span>. Prominent eustachian valve in a 32-year-old woman who presented with chest pain. <b>(a)</b> Subcostal four-chamber view from <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> demonstrates a linear hyperechoic lesion (arrow) in the right atrium. Although this was suspected to represent the eustachian valve, the full extent of the lesion could not be visualized; MR imaging was requested to exclude a mass lesion. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal oblique steady-state free precession (<abbr title="steady-state free precession">SSFP</abbr>) MR image of the heart helps confirm the lesion (arrow) to be the eustachian valve.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160105&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160105/asset/images/large/rg.2017160105.fig13b.jpeg" height="884" width="441" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span>. Prominent eustachian valve in a 32-year-old woman who presented with chest pain. <b>(a)</b> Subcostal four-chamber view from <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> demonstrates a linear hyperechoic lesion (arrow) in the right atrium. Although this was suspected to represent the eustachian valve, the full extent of the lesion could not be visualized; MR imaging was requested to exclude a mass lesion. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal oblique steady-state free precession (<abbr title="steady-state free precession">SSFP</abbr>) MR image of the heart helps confirm the lesion (arrow) to be the eustachian valve.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160105&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160105/asset/images/large/rg.2017160105.fig14a.jpeg" height="741" width="663" aria-labelledby="fig14a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span>. Prominent right ventricular moderator band in a 55-year-old man who presented with new-onset shortness of breath. <b>(a)</b> Apical four-chamber view from <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> shows increased echogenicity (arrow) throughout the right ventricular apical cavity. This was of unclear cause and thought to possibly represent a mass. <b>(b)</b> Four-chamber <abbr title="steady-state free precession">SSFP</abbr> MR image of the heart demonstrates the suspected mass (arrow) to represent a prominent right ventricular moderator band that filled nearly the entire right ventricular apical cavity during end systole.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160105&amp;id=fig14a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160105/asset/images/large/rg.2017160105.fig14b.jpeg" height="741" width="660" aria-labelledby="fig14b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span>. Prominent right ventricular moderator band in a 55-year-old man who presented with new-onset shortness of breath. <b>(a)</b> Apical four-chamber view from <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> shows increased echogenicity (arrow) throughout the right ventricular apical cavity. This was of unclear cause and thought to possibly represent a mass. <b>(b)</b> Four-chamber <abbr title="steady-state free precession">SSFP</abbr> MR image of the heart demonstrates the suspected mass (arrow) to represent a prominent right ventricular moderator band that filled nearly the entire right ventricular apical cavity during end systole.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160105&amp;id=fig14b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160105/asset/images/large/rg.2017160105.fig15a.jpeg" height="692" width="700" aria-labelledby="fig15a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15a</span>. Prominent fat in the right atrioventricular groove in a 45-year-old woman who presented for further workup of an incidental lesion seen at <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr>. <b>(a)</b> Apical four-chamber view from <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> shows a hyperechoic lesion (arrow) along the lateral right atrial wall. <b>(b, c)</b> Four-chamber proton-density–weighted <b>(b)</b> and fat-saturated triple inversion-recovery <b>(c)</b> MR images of the heart at the same level as the <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> demonstrate that the lesion (arrow) drops out in signal on the fat-saturated image, consistent with a fat-containing lesion. The constellation of findings was most consistent with prominent fat in the right atrioventricular groove.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160105&amp;id=fig15a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160105/asset/images/large/rg.2017160105.fig15b.jpeg" height="587" width="650" aria-labelledby="fig15b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15b</span>. Prominent fat in the right atrioventricular groove in a 45-year-old woman who presented for further workup of an incidental lesion seen at <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr>. <b>(a)</b> Apical four-chamber view from <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> shows a hyperechoic lesion (arrow) along the lateral right atrial wall. <b>(b, c)</b> Four-chamber proton-density–weighted <b>(b)</b> and fat-saturated triple inversion-recovery <b>(c)</b> MR images of the heart at the same level as the <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> demonstrate that the lesion (arrow) drops out in signal on the fat-saturated image, consistent with a fat-containing lesion. The constellation of findings was most consistent with prominent fat in the right atrioventricular groove.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160105&amp;id=fig15b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160105/asset/images/large/rg.2017160105.fig15c.jpeg" height="587" width="676" aria-labelledby="fig15c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15c</span>. Prominent fat in the right atrioventricular groove in a 45-year-old woman who presented for further workup of an incidental lesion seen at <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr>. <b>(a)</b> Apical four-chamber view from <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> shows a hyperechoic lesion (arrow) along the lateral right atrial wall. <b>(b, c)</b> Four-chamber proton-density–weighted <b>(b)</b> and fat-saturated triple inversion-recovery <b>(c)</b> MR images of the heart at the same level as the <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> demonstrate that the lesion (arrow) drops out in signal on the fat-saturated image, consistent with a fat-containing lesion. The constellation of findings was most consistent with prominent fat in the right atrioventricular groove.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160105&amp;id=fig15c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160105/asset/images/large/rg.2017160105.fig16a.jpeg" height="763" width="581" aria-labelledby="fig16a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span>. Thickened left ventricular fibromuscular band in a 74-year-old man with a history of coronary artery disease and reduced left ventricular systolic function. <b>(a)</b> Apical four-chamber view from <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> demonstrates an irregularly shaped hyperechoic lesion (arrow) partially crossing the left ventricular cavity. A left ventricular band was in the differential diagnosis, but given the patient’s reduced systolic function, the thick appearance of the lesion, and the inability to definitively visualize a connection with the left ventricular free wall, the patient was referred for further evaluation with cardiac CT. The patient was severely claustrophobic and declined to attempt cardiac MR imaging. <b>(b)</b> Four-chamber reformatted ECG-gated CT angiogram shows the left ventricular lesion (arrows) to be a slightly thickened left ventricular fibromuscular band clearly noted to be crossing the left ventricle from the interventricular septum to the free wall.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160105&amp;id=fig16a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160105/asset/images/large/rg.2017160105.fig16b.jpeg" height="763" width="643" aria-labelledby="fig16b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span>. Thickened left ventricular fibromuscular band in a 74-year-old man with a history of coronary artery disease and reduced left ventricular systolic function. <b>(a)</b> Apical four-chamber view from <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> demonstrates an irregularly shaped hyperechoic lesion (arrow) partially crossing the left ventricular cavity. A left ventricular band was in the differential diagnosis, but given the patient’s reduced systolic function, the thick appearance of the lesion, and the inability to definitively visualize a connection with the left ventricular free wall, the patient was referred for further evaluation with cardiac CT. The patient was severely claustrophobic and declined to attempt cardiac MR imaging. <b>(b)</b> Four-chamber reformatted ECG-gated CT angiogram shows the left ventricular lesion (arrows) to be a slightly thickened left ventricular fibromuscular band clearly noted to be crossing the left ventricle from the interventricular septum to the free wall.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160105&amp;id=fig16b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160105/asset/images/large/rg.2017160105.fig17a.jpeg" height="753" width="606" aria-labelledby="fig17a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17a</span>. Large hiatal hernia displacing the left atrium in an 80-year-old woman who presented with new-onset lower extremity edema. <b>(a)</b> Apical four-chamber view from <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> demonstrates an apparent hyperechoic mass (arrow) in the left atrium. <b>(b)</b> Two-chamber <abbr title="steady-state free precession">SSFP</abbr> MR image of the heart demonstrates that the apparent left atrial mass (arrow) is a large hiatal hernia superiorly displacing the left atrium. The <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> findings were attributed to volume averaging of the hiatal hernia.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160105&amp;id=fig17a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160105/asset/images/large/rg.2017160105.fig17b.jpeg" height="753" width="719" aria-labelledby="fig17b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17b</span>. Large hiatal hernia displacing the left atrium in an 80-year-old woman who presented with new-onset lower extremity edema. <b>(a)</b> Apical four-chamber view from <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> demonstrates an apparent hyperechoic mass (arrow) in the left atrium. <b>(b)</b> Two-chamber <abbr title="steady-state free precession">SSFP</abbr> MR image of the heart demonstrates that the apparent left atrial mass (arrow) is a large hiatal hernia superiorly displacing the left atrium. The <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> findings were attributed to volume averaging of the hiatal hernia.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160105&amp;id=fig17b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160105/asset/images/large/rg.2017160105.fig18a.jpeg" height="675" width="589" aria-labelledby="fig18a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18a</span>. Mitral annular calcification in a 58-year-old woman who presented with fevers and leukocytosis. <b>(a)</b> Apical four-chamber view from <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> demonstrates a hyperechoic mass (arrow) that appears to be attached to the mitral valve. This was initially thought to represent a myxoma, vegetation, or thrombus. <b>(b)</b> Axial image of the heart from CT without ECG gating or contrast enhancement shows the lesion (arrow) to be densely calcified, consistent with the final diagnosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160105&amp;id=fig18a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160105/asset/images/large/rg.2017160105.fig18b.jpeg" height="674" width="636" aria-labelledby="fig18b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18b</span>. Mitral annular calcification in a 58-year-old woman who presented with fevers and leukocytosis. <b>(a)</b> Apical four-chamber view from <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> demonstrates a hyperechoic mass (arrow) that appears to be attached to the mitral valve. This was initially thought to represent a myxoma, vegetation, or thrombus. <b>(b)</b> Axial image of the heart from CT without ECG gating or contrast enhancement shows the lesion (arrow) to be densely calcified, consistent with the final diagnosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160105&amp;id=fig18b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160105/asset/images/large/rg.2017160105.fig19a.jpeg" height="554" width="559" aria-labelledby="fig19a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19a</span>. Lipomatous hypertrophy of the interatrial septum in a 74-year-old obese man with a history of renal cell carcinoma and new-onset shortness of breath. <b>(a)</b> Subcostal four-chamber view from <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> shows a hyperechoic mass (arrows) in the interatrial septum. This was suspected to represent lipomatous hypertrophy of the interatrial septum on the basis of its dumbbell-shaped configuration, but CT was requested for definitive evaluation given the patient’s history of renal cell cancer. <b>(b)</b> Four-chamber image of the heart from nongated nonenhanced CT shows the interatrial lesion (arrows) to be composed of fat, confirming the suspected diagnosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160105&amp;id=fig19a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160105/asset/images/large/rg.2017160105.fig19b.jpeg" height="554" width="567" aria-labelledby="fig19b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19b</span>. Lipomatous hypertrophy of the interatrial septum in a 74-year-old obese man with a history of renal cell carcinoma and new-onset shortness of breath. <b>(a)</b> Subcostal four-chamber view from <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> shows a hyperechoic mass (arrows) in the interatrial septum. This was suspected to represent lipomatous hypertrophy of the interatrial septum on the basis of its dumbbell-shaped configuration, but CT was requested for definitive evaluation given the patient’s history of renal cell cancer. <b>(b)</b> Four-chamber image of the heart from nongated nonenhanced CT shows the interatrial lesion (arrows) to be composed of fat, confirming the suspected diagnosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160105&amp;id=fig19b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160105/asset/images/large/rg.2017160105.fig20a.jpeg" height="701" width="600" aria-labelledby="fig20a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20a</span>. Calcified thrombus in a 61-year-old woman with a history of tricuspid regurgitation. <b>(a)</b> Apical four-chamber view from <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> demonstrates a peripherally hyperechoic and centrally hypoechoic mass (arrow) in the right atrium. A stalk was not clearly seen. The differential diagnosis at <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> was led by myxoma and thrombus. <b>(b)</b> Axial image of the heart from nongated contrast-enhanced CT demonstrates a peripherally calcified mass in the right atrium that appears to be attached to the interatrial septum (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Axial postcontrast long inversion time (600 msec) MR image of the heart does not show enhancement within the mass (arrow). The constellation of findings was consistent with a chronic peripherally calcified thrombus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160105&amp;id=fig20a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160105/asset/images/large/rg.2017160105.fig20b.jpeg" height="571" width="635" aria-labelledby="fig20b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20b</span>. Calcified thrombus in a 61-year-old woman with a history of tricuspid regurgitation. <b>(a)</b> Apical four-chamber view from <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> demonstrates a peripherally hyperechoic and centrally hypoechoic mass (arrow) in the right atrium. A stalk was not clearly seen. The differential diagnosis at <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> was led by myxoma and thrombus. <b>(b)</b> Axial image of the heart from nongated contrast-enhanced CT demonstrates a peripherally calcified mass in the right atrium that appears to be attached to the interatrial septum (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Axial postcontrast long inversion time (600 msec) MR image of the heart does not show enhancement within the mass (arrow). The constellation of findings was consistent with a chronic peripherally calcified thrombus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160105&amp;id=fig20b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160105/asset/images/large/rg.2017160105.fig20c.jpeg" height="571" width="665" aria-labelledby="fig20c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20c</span>. Calcified thrombus in a 61-year-old woman with a history of tricuspid regurgitation. <b>(a)</b> Apical four-chamber view from <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> demonstrates a peripherally hyperechoic and centrally hypoechoic mass (arrow) in the right atrium. A stalk was not clearly seen. The differential diagnosis at <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> was led by myxoma and thrombus. <b>(b)</b> Axial image of the heart from nongated contrast-enhanced CT demonstrates a peripherally calcified mass in the right atrium that appears to be attached to the interatrial septum (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Axial postcontrast long inversion time (600 msec) MR image of the heart does not show enhancement within the mass (arrow). The constellation of findings was consistent with a chronic peripherally calcified thrombus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160105&amp;id=fig20c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160105/asset/images/large/rg.2017160105.fig21a.jpeg" height="485" width="719" aria-labelledby="fig21a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21a</span>. Probable cardiac fibroma in a 14-year-old boy presenting with new-onset shortness of breath. <b>(a)</b> Oblique apical four-chamber view from <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> demonstrates a hyperechoic mass (arrow) in the lateral left ventricular wall with mass effect on, or extension into, the left ventricular cavity. <b>(b)</b> Axial <abbr title="steady-state free precession">SSFP</abbr> MR image at the level of the ventricles demonstrates the mass (arrow) to be in the lateral left ventricular wall. <b>(c)</b> Axial T2-weighted image with fat saturation at the same level demonstrates the mass (long arrow) to be hypointense to the myocardium (short arrows). <b>(d)</b> Axial immediately postcontrast MR image does not demonstrate significant enhancement of the mass (long arrow) relative to the myocardium (short arrows). <b>(e)</b> Axial delayed postcontrast MR image at the same level demonstrates avid enhancement of the mass (long arrow) relative to the myocardium (short arrows). Key findings of a solitary mass hypointense to myocardium on T2-weighted images and avid enhancement of the mass on delayed postcontrast images in conjunction with the patient’s age being greater than 4 years (recall that most rhabdomyomas spontaneously regress by 4 years of age) are most consistent with a cardiac fibroma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160105&amp;id=fig21a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160105/asset/images/large/rg.2017160105.fig21b.jpeg" height="485" width="605" aria-labelledby="fig21b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21b</span>. Probable cardiac fibroma in a 14-year-old boy presenting with new-onset shortness of breath. <b>(a)</b> Oblique apical four-chamber view from <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> demonstrates a hyperechoic mass (arrow) in the lateral left ventricular wall with mass effect on, or extension into, the left ventricular cavity. <b>(b)</b> Axial <abbr title="steady-state free precession">SSFP</abbr> MR image at the level of the ventricles demonstrates the mass (arrow) to be in the lateral left ventricular wall. <b>(c)</b> Axial T2-weighted image with fat saturation at the same level demonstrates the mass (long arrow) to be hypointense to the myocardium (short arrows). <b>(d)</b> Axial immediately postcontrast MR image does not demonstrate significant enhancement of the mass (long arrow) relative to the myocardium (short arrows). <b>(e)</b> Axial delayed postcontrast MR image at the same level demonstrates avid enhancement of the mass (long arrow) relative to the myocardium (short arrows). Key findings of a solitary mass hypointense to myocardium on T2-weighted images and avid enhancement of the mass on delayed postcontrast images in conjunction with the patient’s age being greater than 4 years (recall that most rhabdomyomas spontaneously regress by 4 years of age) are most consistent with a cardiac fibroma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160105&amp;id=fig21b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160105/asset/images/large/rg.2017160105.fig21c.jpeg" height="544" width="615" aria-labelledby="fig21c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21c</span>. Probable cardiac fibroma in a 14-year-old boy presenting with new-onset shortness of breath. <b>(a)</b> Oblique apical four-chamber view from <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> demonstrates a hyperechoic mass (arrow) in the lateral left ventricular wall with mass effect on, or extension into, the left ventricular cavity. <b>(b)</b> Axial <abbr title="steady-state free precession">SSFP</abbr> MR image at the level of the ventricles demonstrates the mass (arrow) to be in the lateral left ventricular wall. <b>(c)</b> Axial T2-weighted image with fat saturation at the same level demonstrates the mass (long arrow) to be hypointense to the myocardium (short arrows). <b>(d)</b> Axial immediately postcontrast MR image does not demonstrate significant enhancement of the mass (long arrow) relative to the myocardium (short arrows). <b>(e)</b> Axial delayed postcontrast MR image at the same level demonstrates avid enhancement of the mass (long arrow) relative to the myocardium (short arrows). Key findings of a solitary mass hypointense to myocardium on T2-weighted images and avid enhancement of the mass on delayed postcontrast images in conjunction with the patient’s age being greater than 4 years (recall that most rhabdomyomas spontaneously regress by 4 years of age) are most consistent with a cardiac fibroma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160105&amp;id=fig21c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160105/asset/images/large/rg.2017160105.fig21d.jpeg" height="544" width="620" aria-labelledby="fig21d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21d</span>. Probable cardiac fibroma in a 14-year-old boy presenting with new-onset shortness of breath. <b>(a)</b> Oblique apical four-chamber view from <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> demonstrates a hyperechoic mass (arrow) in the lateral left ventricular wall with mass effect on, or extension into, the left ventricular cavity. <b>(b)</b> Axial <abbr title="steady-state free precession">SSFP</abbr> MR image at the level of the ventricles demonstrates the mass (arrow) to be in the lateral left ventricular wall. <b>(c)</b> Axial T2-weighted image with fat saturation at the same level demonstrates the mass (long arrow) to be hypointense to the myocardium (short arrows). <b>(d)</b> Axial immediately postcontrast MR image does not demonstrate significant enhancement of the mass (long arrow) relative to the myocardium (short arrows). <b>(e)</b> Axial delayed postcontrast MR image at the same level demonstrates avid enhancement of the mass (long arrow) relative to the myocardium (short arrows). Key findings of a solitary mass hypointense to myocardium on T2-weighted images and avid enhancement of the mass on delayed postcontrast images in conjunction with the patient’s age being greater than 4 years (recall that most rhabdomyomas spontaneously regress by 4 years of age) are most consistent with a cardiac fibroma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160105&amp;id=fig21d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160105/asset/images/large/rg.2017160105.fig21e.jpeg" height="544" width="617" aria-labelledby="fig21e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21e</span>. Probable cardiac fibroma in a 14-year-old boy presenting with new-onset shortness of breath. <b>(a)</b> Oblique apical four-chamber view from <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> demonstrates a hyperechoic mass (arrow) in the lateral left ventricular wall with mass effect on, or extension into, the left ventricular cavity. <b>(b)</b> Axial <abbr title="steady-state free precession">SSFP</abbr> MR image at the level of the ventricles demonstrates the mass (arrow) to be in the lateral left ventricular wall. <b>(c)</b> Axial T2-weighted image with fat saturation at the same level demonstrates the mass (long arrow) to be hypointense to the myocardium (short arrows). <b>(d)</b> Axial immediately postcontrast MR image does not demonstrate significant enhancement of the mass (long arrow) relative to the myocardium (short arrows). <b>(e)</b> Axial delayed postcontrast MR image at the same level demonstrates avid enhancement of the mass (long arrow) relative to the myocardium (short arrows). Key findings of a solitary mass hypointense to myocardium on T2-weighted images and avid enhancement of the mass on delayed postcontrast images in conjunction with the patient’s age being greater than 4 years (recall that most rhabdomyomas spontaneously regress by 4 years of age) are most consistent with a cardiac fibroma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160105&amp;id=fig21e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160105/asset/images/large/rg.2017160105.fig22a.jpeg" height="803" width="626" aria-labelledby="fig22a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22a</span>. Primary cardiac angiosarcoma in a 29-year-old man presenting with severe shortness of breath and new-onset lower-extremity edema. <b>(a)</b> Apical four-chamber view from <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> shows a small pericardial effusion (short arrows) and a hyperechoic mass (long arrow) with lobulated margins in the right atrium. There is possible extension into the right atrial wall. Malignancy was suspected given the small pericardial effusion, possible invasion into the right atrial wall, and lobulated margins of the mass. The patient was referred for cardiac MR imaging to better visualize and characterize the mass. <b>(b)</b> Four-chamber <abbr title="steady-state free precession">SSFP</abbr> MR image demonstrates a right atrial mass invading the right atrial wall (long arrow) with lobulated margins and a small pericardial effusion (short arrows). Given the absence of a known extracardiac malignancy, the constellation of findings was most suggestive of a primary cardiac angiosarcoma. This was later proven at pathologic examination following autopsy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160105&amp;id=fig22a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160105/asset/images/large/rg.2017160105.fig22b.jpeg" height="803" width="599" aria-labelledby="fig22b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22b</span>. Primary cardiac angiosarcoma in a 29-year-old man presenting with severe shortness of breath and new-onset lower-extremity edema. <b>(a)</b> Apical four-chamber view from <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> shows a small pericardial effusion (short arrows) and a hyperechoic mass (long arrow) with lobulated margins in the right atrium. There is possible extension into the right atrial wall. Malignancy was suspected given the small pericardial effusion, possible invasion into the right atrial wall, and lobulated margins of the mass. The patient was referred for cardiac MR imaging to better visualize and characterize the mass. <b>(b)</b> Four-chamber <abbr title="steady-state free precession">SSFP</abbr> MR image demonstrates a right atrial mass invading the right atrial wall (long arrow) with lobulated margins and a small pericardial effusion (short arrows). Given the absence of a known extracardiac malignancy, the constellation of findings was most suggestive of a primary cardiac angiosarcoma. This was later proven at pathologic examination following autopsy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160105&amp;id=fig22b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160105/asset/images/large/rg.2017160105.fig23a.jpeg" height="802" width="573" aria-labelledby="fig23a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23a</span>. Left ventricular apical aneurysm in a 74-year-old woman with a history of coronary artery disease and myocardial infarction. <i>Ao</i> = ascending thoracic aorta. <b>(a)</b> Apical long-axis view from <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> demonstrates what appears to be a normal left ventricular apex (arrow). Recall that the apical long-axis view typically demonstrates the left ventricular apex. <b>(b)</b> Three-chamber <abbr title="steady-state free precession">SSFP</abbr> MR image of the heart demonstrates a small left ventricular apical aneurysm (arrow) not seen at <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr>. This was thought to be out of the imaging plane on the apical long-axis view.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160105&amp;id=fig23a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160105/asset/images/large/rg.2017160105.fig23b.jpeg" height="802" width="654" aria-labelledby="fig23b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23b</span>. Left ventricular apical aneurysm in a 74-year-old woman with a history of coronary artery disease and myocardial infarction. <i>Ao</i> = ascending thoracic aorta. <b>(a)</b> Apical long-axis view from <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> demonstrates what appears to be a normal left ventricular apex (arrow). Recall that the apical long-axis view typically demonstrates the left ventricular apex. <b>(b)</b> Three-chamber <abbr title="steady-state free precession">SSFP</abbr> MR image of the heart demonstrates a small left ventricular apical aneurysm (arrow) not seen at <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr>. This was thought to be out of the imaging plane on the apical long-axis view.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160105&amp;id=fig23b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig24a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160105/asset/images/large/rg.2017160105.fig24a.jpeg" height="616" width="373" aria-labelledby="fig24a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 24a</span>. Apical infarct in a 47-year-old woman who presented with chest pain the day after her husband died in a motor vehicle accident. She was diagnosed with a non–ST segment elevation myocardial infarction and underwent left heart catheterization, which demonstrated normal results. <b>(a)</b> Apical two-chamber view from <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> demonstrates apical ballooning (arrow). Cine images (Movie 1) from <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> also demonstrated apical hypokinesis. Given the normal left heart catheterization, apical ballooning, and apical hypokinesis, the patient was presumptively diagnosed with Takotsubo (or stress) cardiomyopathy related to her husband’s recent death. However, the patient had recurrent episodes of chest pain and persistently rising serum troponins, so the differential diagnosis was broadened to include coronary artery vasospasm, recanalized coronary artery occlusion, and myocarditis. The patient was referred for cardiac MR imaging for further evaluation. <b>(b, c)</b> Two-chamber <b>(b)</b> and four-chamber <b>(c)</b> late gadolinium enhancement MR images of the heart demonstrate transmural enhancement of the apex with central areas of hypoattenuation, consistent with apical infarct, with areas (arrows) of microvascular obstruction. Cine MR images (Movie 2) also showed mild apical ballooning and hypokinesis, in concordance with the <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> findings. On the basis of the additional information provided at MR imaging, the patient was diagnosed with an apical infarct secondary to vasospasm or to a recanalized coronary artery occlusion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160105&amp;id=fig24a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig24b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160105/asset/images/large/rg.2017160105.fig24b.jpeg" height="616" width="831" aria-labelledby="fig24b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 24b</span>. Apical infarct in a 47-year-old woman who presented with chest pain the day after her husband died in a motor vehicle accident. She was diagnosed with a non–ST segment elevation myocardial infarction and underwent left heart catheterization, which demonstrated normal results. <b>(a)</b> Apical two-chamber view from <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> demonstrates apical ballooning (arrow). Cine images (Movie 1) from <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> also demonstrated apical hypokinesis. Given the normal left heart catheterization, apical ballooning, and apical hypokinesis, the patient was presumptively diagnosed with Takotsubo (or stress) cardiomyopathy related to her husband’s recent death. However, the patient had recurrent episodes of chest pain and persistently rising serum troponins, so the differential diagnosis was broadened to include coronary artery vasospasm, recanalized coronary artery occlusion, and myocarditis. The patient was referred for cardiac MR imaging for further evaluation. <b>(b, c)</b> Two-chamber <b>(b)</b> and four-chamber <b>(c)</b> late gadolinium enhancement MR images of the heart demonstrate transmural enhancement of the apex with central areas of hypoattenuation, consistent with apical infarct, with areas (arrows) of microvascular obstruction. Cine MR images (Movie 2) also showed mild apical ballooning and hypokinesis, in concordance with the <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> findings. On the basis of the additional information provided at MR imaging, the patient was diagnosed with an apical infarct secondary to vasospasm or to a recanalized coronary artery occlusion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160105&amp;id=fig24b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig24c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160105/asset/images/large/rg.2017160105.fig24c.jpeg" height="616" width="446" aria-labelledby="fig24c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 24c</span>. Apical infarct in a 47-year-old woman who presented with chest pain the day after her husband died in a motor vehicle accident. She was diagnosed with a non–ST segment elevation myocardial infarction and underwent left heart catheterization, which demonstrated normal results. <b>(a)</b> Apical two-chamber view from <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> demonstrates apical ballooning (arrow). Cine images (Movie 1) from <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> also demonstrated apical hypokinesis. Given the normal left heart catheterization, apical ballooning, and apical hypokinesis, the patient was presumptively diagnosed with Takotsubo (or stress) cardiomyopathy related to her husband’s recent death. However, the patient had recurrent episodes of chest pain and persistently rising serum troponins, so the differential diagnosis was broadened to include coronary artery vasospasm, recanalized coronary artery occlusion, and myocarditis. The patient was referred for cardiac MR imaging for further evaluation. <b>(b, c)</b> Two-chamber <b>(b)</b> and four-chamber <b>(c)</b> late gadolinium enhancement MR images of the heart demonstrate transmural enhancement of the apex with central areas of hypoattenuation, consistent with apical infarct, with areas (arrows) of microvascular obstruction. Cine MR images (Movie 2) also showed mild apical ballooning and hypokinesis, in concordance with the <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> findings. On the basis of the additional information provided at MR imaging, the patient was diagnosed with an apical infarct secondary to vasospasm or to a recanalized coronary artery occlusion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160105&amp;id=fig24c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig25a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160105/asset/images/large/rg.2017160105.fig25a.jpeg" height="843" width="598" aria-labelledby="fig25a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 25a</span>. Apical hypertrophic cardiomyopathy in a 63-year-old woman presenting with palpitations and an electrocardiogram suspicious for hypertrophic cardiomyopathy. <b>(a)</b> Apical four-chamber view from <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> does not fully demonstrate the left ventricular apex (arrow) due to poor acoustic windows. The distal septal wall was noted to be thickened, supporting a clinical diagnosis of hypertrophic cardiomyopathy. However, MR imaging was requested for visualization of the apex and to better delineate the left ventricular wall. <b>(b)</b> Four-chamber <abbr title="steady-state free precession">SSFP</abbr> MR image of the heart clearly demonstrates circumferential apical wall thickening not appreciated at <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr>. Findings were consistent with an apical variant of hypertrophic cardiomyopathy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160105&amp;id=fig25a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig25b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160105/asset/images/large/rg.2017160105.fig25b.jpeg" height="843" width="628" aria-labelledby="fig25b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 25b</span>. Apical hypertrophic cardiomyopathy in a 63-year-old woman presenting with palpitations and an electrocardiogram suspicious for hypertrophic cardiomyopathy. <b>(a)</b> Apical four-chamber view from <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> does not fully demonstrate the left ventricular apex (arrow) due to poor acoustic windows. The distal septal wall was noted to be thickened, supporting a clinical diagnosis of hypertrophic cardiomyopathy. However, MR imaging was requested for visualization of the apex and to better delineate the left ventricular wall. <b>(b)</b> Four-chamber <abbr title="steady-state free precession">SSFP</abbr> MR image of the heart clearly demonstrates circumferential apical wall thickening not appreciated at <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr>. Findings were consistent with an apical variant of hypertrophic cardiomyopathy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160105&amp;id=fig25b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig26a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160105/asset/images/large/rg.2017160105.fig26a.jpeg" height="684" width="632" aria-labelledby="fig26a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 26a</span>. Cardiac amyloidosis in a 59-year-old woman with a new diagnosis of heart failure and a family history of gene-positive transthyretin-related amyloidosis. <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> showed mild hypertrophy of the interventricular septum, left ventricular enlargement, and mildly reduced systolic function of 45% (not shown). These findings were nonspecific as to the cause of the patient’s heart failure. She was referred for cardiac MR imaging for further evaluation, particularly given her family history. <b>(a)</b> Four-chamber <abbr title="steady-state free precession">SSFP</abbr> MR image shows mild thickening (arrow) of the interventricular septum and left ventricular enlargement, which were also seen at <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr>. Cine MR images also demonstrated mildly reduced systolic function. <b>(b)</b> Short-axis late gadolinium enhancement MR image at the midventricular level demonstrates nearly circumferential left ventricular subendocardial enhancement (short arrows), enhancement on the right ventricular side of the interventricular septum (long arrows), and enhancement of the anterior wall of the right ventricle (arrowhead). Also note the nearly complete absence of contrast material in the blood pool, suggestive of an expanded total body extravascular space (the image was obtained approximately 2–3 minutes after contrast material administration). The constellation of findings was most consistent with cardiac involvement of amyloidosis as the cause of the patient’s new-onset heart failure.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160105&amp;id=fig26a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig26b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160105/asset/images/large/rg.2017160105.fig26b.jpeg" height="684" width="593" aria-labelledby="fig26b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 26b</span>. Cardiac amyloidosis in a 59-year-old woman with a new diagnosis of heart failure and a family history of gene-positive transthyretin-related amyloidosis. <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> showed mild hypertrophy of the interventricular septum, left ventricular enlargement, and mildly reduced systolic function of 45% (not shown). These findings were nonspecific as to the cause of the patient’s heart failure. She was referred for cardiac MR imaging for further evaluation, particularly given her family history. <b>(a)</b> Four-chamber <abbr title="steady-state free precession">SSFP</abbr> MR image shows mild thickening (arrow) of the interventricular septum and left ventricular enlargement, which were also seen at <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr>. Cine MR images also demonstrated mildly reduced systolic function. <b>(b)</b> Short-axis late gadolinium enhancement MR image at the midventricular level demonstrates nearly circumferential left ventricular subendocardial enhancement (short arrows), enhancement on the right ventricular side of the interventricular septum (long arrows), and enhancement of the anterior wall of the right ventricle (arrowhead). Also note the nearly complete absence of contrast material in the blood pool, suggestive of an expanded total body extravascular space (the image was obtained approximately 2–3 minutes after contrast material administration). The constellation of findings was most consistent with cardiac involvement of amyloidosis as the cause of the patient’s new-onset heart failure.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160105&amp;id=fig26b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig27a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160105/asset/images/large/rg.2017160105.fig27a.jpeg" height="552" width="733" aria-labelledby="fig27a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 27a</span>. Probable reverberation artifact in a 72-year-old woman who presented with chest pain. <i>Ao</i> = ascending thoracic aorta. <b>(a)</b> Parasternal long-axis view from <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> demonstrates linear echogenicity (arrow) in the ascending aorta worrisome for aortic dissection. <b>(b)</b> Three-chamber view of the heart from CT angiography performed for preoperative planning is normal and does not show thoracic aortic dissection. The findings at <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> were thought to be secondary to reverberation artifact.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160105&amp;id=fig27a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig27b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160105/asset/images/large/rg.2017160105.fig27b.jpeg" height="552" width="743" aria-labelledby="fig27b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 27b</span>. Probable reverberation artifact in a 72-year-old woman who presented with chest pain. <i>Ao</i> = ascending thoracic aorta. <b>(a)</b> Parasternal long-axis view from <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> demonstrates linear echogenicity (arrow) in the ascending aorta worrisome for aortic dissection. <b>(b)</b> Three-chamber view of the heart from CT angiography performed for preoperative planning is normal and does not show thoracic aortic dissection. The findings at <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> were thought to be secondary to reverberation artifact.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160105&amp;id=fig27b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig28a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160105/asset/images/large/rg.2017160105.fig28a.jpeg" height="531" width="749" aria-labelledby="fig28a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 28a</span>. Ascending thoracic aortic dissection not clearly visualized at <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> in a 62-year-old woman who presented with severe chest pain. <i>Ao</i> = ascending aorta. <b>(a)</b> Parasternal long-axis view from <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> does not clearly demonstrate a linear echogenicity in the ascending aorta to suggest an ascending thoracic aortic dissection. <b>(b)</b> Image from nongated CT angiography of the chest reformatted to match the <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> clearly demonstrates an ascending (white arrow) and descending (black arrow) thoracic aortic dissection. The CT was performed shortly after the <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> due to persistent severe chest pain. The false-negative <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> was attributed to poor acoustic windows and image noise.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160105&amp;id=fig28a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig28b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160105/asset/images/large/rg.2017160105.fig28b.jpeg" height="532" width="726" aria-labelledby="fig28b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 28b</span>. Ascending thoracic aortic dissection not clearly visualized at <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> in a 62-year-old woman who presented with severe chest pain. <i>Ao</i> = ascending aorta. <b>(a)</b> Parasternal long-axis view from <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> does not clearly demonstrate a linear echogenicity in the ascending aorta to suggest an ascending thoracic aortic dissection. <b>(b)</b> Image from nongated CT angiography of the chest reformatted to match the <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> clearly demonstrates an ascending (white arrow) and descending (black arrow) thoracic aortic dissection. The CT was performed shortly after the <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> due to persistent severe chest pain. The false-negative <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> was attributed to poor acoustic windows and image noise.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160105&amp;id=fig28b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig29a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160105/asset/images/large/rg.2017160105.fig29a.jpeg" height="664" width="569" aria-labelledby="fig29a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 29a</span>. Pericardial lipomatosis in a 50-year-old woman who presented with chest pain. <b>(a)</b> Parasternal short-axis view from <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> at the midventricular level demonstrates a large area of increased echogenicity (arrow) in the pericardial space inferior to the left ventricle. This was thought to represent a large hemorrhagic pericardial effusion. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image through the heart demonstrates extensive pericardial fat deposition (arrows), consistent with pericardial lipomatosis. <b>(c)</b> Axial proton-density–weighted MR image demonstrates relatively homogeneous hyperintensity (arrows) throughout the pericardial space. <b>(d)</b> T2-weighted fat-saturated MR image at the same level shows signal suppression (arrows) in the pericardial space, consistent with the presence of fat. The MR imaging findings were consistent with pericardial lipomatosis, as seen at CT.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160105&amp;id=fig29a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig29b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160105/asset/images/large/rg.2017160105.fig29b.jpeg" height="664" width="756" aria-labelledby="fig29b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 29b</span>. Pericardial lipomatosis in a 50-year-old woman who presented with chest pain. <b>(a)</b> Parasternal short-axis view from <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> at the midventricular level demonstrates a large area of increased echogenicity (arrow) in the pericardial space inferior to the left ventricle. This was thought to represent a large hemorrhagic pericardial effusion. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image through the heart demonstrates extensive pericardial fat deposition (arrows), consistent with pericardial lipomatosis. <b>(c)</b> Axial proton-density–weighted MR image demonstrates relatively homogeneous hyperintensity (arrows) throughout the pericardial space. <b>(d)</b> T2-weighted fat-saturated MR image at the same level shows signal suppression (arrows) in the pericardial space, consistent with the presence of fat. The MR imaging findings were consistent with pericardial lipomatosis, as seen at CT.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160105&amp;id=fig29b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig29c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160105/asset/images/large/rg.2017160105.fig29c.jpeg" height="537" width="626" aria-labelledby="fig29c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 29c</span>. Pericardial lipomatosis in a 50-year-old woman who presented with chest pain. <b>(a)</b> Parasternal short-axis view from <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> at the midventricular level demonstrates a large area of increased echogenicity (arrow) in the pericardial space inferior to the left ventricle. This was thought to represent a large hemorrhagic pericardial effusion. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image through the heart demonstrates extensive pericardial fat deposition (arrows), consistent with pericardial lipomatosis. <b>(c)</b> Axial proton-density–weighted MR image demonstrates relatively homogeneous hyperintensity (arrows) throughout the pericardial space. <b>(d)</b> T2-weighted fat-saturated MR image at the same level shows signal suppression (arrows) in the pericardial space, consistent with the presence of fat. The MR imaging findings were consistent with pericardial lipomatosis, as seen at CT.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160105&amp;id=fig29c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig29d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160105/asset/images/large/rg.2017160105.fig29d.jpeg" height="537" width="699" aria-labelledby="fig29d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 29d</span>. Pericardial lipomatosis in a 50-year-old woman who presented with chest pain. <b>(a)</b> Parasternal short-axis view from <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> at the midventricular level demonstrates a large area of increased echogenicity (arrow) in the pericardial space inferior to the left ventricle. This was thought to represent a large hemorrhagic pericardial effusion. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image through the heart demonstrates extensive pericardial fat deposition (arrows), consistent with pericardial lipomatosis. <b>(c)</b> Axial proton-density–weighted MR image demonstrates relatively homogeneous hyperintensity (arrows) throughout the pericardial space. <b>(d)</b> T2-weighted fat-saturated MR image at the same level shows signal suppression (arrows) in the pericardial space, consistent with the presence of fat. The MR imaging findings were consistent with pericardial lipomatosis, as seen at CT.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160105&amp;id=fig29d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig30" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160105/asset/images/large/rg.2017160105.fig30.jpeg" height="769" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig30" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 30</span>. Constrictive pericarditis, which was suspected at <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr>, in a 50-year-old man. Axial nonenhanced CT image through the heart demonstrates pericardial calcifications (arrows), supporting the diagnosis. The calcifications were not appreciated at <abbr title="transthoracic echocardiography">TTE</abbr> (not shown).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160105&amp;id=fig30">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Terpenning S, White CS. Imaging pitfalls, normal anatomy, and anatomical variants that can simulate disease on cardiac imaging as demonstrated on multidetector computed tomography. <em>Acta Radiol Short Rep</em> 2015;4(1): 2047981614562443.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1177/2047981614562443">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Imaging+pitfalls%2C+normal+anatomy%2C+and+anatomical+variants+that+can+simulate+disease+on+cardiac+imaging+as+demonstrated+on+multidetector+computed+tomography&amp;author=S+Terpenning&amp;author=CS+White&amp;publication_year=2015&amp;journal=Acta+Radiol+Short+Rep&amp;pages=2047981614562443&amp;doi=10.1177%2F2047981614562443">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="r2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Prakken NH, Teske AJ, Cramer MJ, et al. Head-to-head comparison between echocardiography and cardiac MRI in the evaluation of the athlete’s heart. <em>Br J Sports Med</em> 2012;46(5):348–354.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1136/bjsm.2010.077669">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21278426/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Head-to-head+comparison+between+echocardiography+and+cardiac+MRI+in+the+evaluation+of+the+athlete%E2%80%99s+heart&amp;author=NH+Prakken&amp;author=AJ+Teske&amp;author=MJ+Cramer&amp;publication_year=2012&amp;journal=Br+J+Sports+Med&amp;pages=348-354&amp;doi=10.1136%2Fbjsm.2010.077669&amp;pmid=21278426">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">3.</div><div id="r3" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-